  "instructions": "Write a ~30-minute episode 2 of the daily local-politics podcast for 2026-05-16. Topic: 'Maryland & Politicians'.\n\nFORMAT:\n  • Two hosts ALEX (presenter) and JORDAN (curious co-host).\n  • Every line starts `ALEX:` or `JORDAN:` — no stage directions, no markdown, no emoji, no '[laughs]', no asterisks.\n  • LENGTH TARGET — 3900 words (±300; ~30 min at 130 wpm).\n  • Cover the segments in `context.segments` in order. Each segment is a topic + a list of events (title, summary, url, date, level, politicians, role/stance). Cite specific votes and dates from the events — generalities are why prior drafts felt repetitive.\n\nPM LENGTH CALIBRATION (read this before drafting):\n  • Recent shipped word counts: no shipped baseline yet.\n  • No prior scripts to calibrate against. Aim for ~3900 words (~30 min).\n  • Hit the target. If you finish all the segments early, EXTEND     the candidate-history reads and the JORDAN pushbacks rather     than wrap; if a segment is bleeding length, tighten it without     losing specific citations.\n\nAVOID — do not reuse any framing on `context.avoid_list`. The PM agent has flagged these as already-shipped this week:\n  - The framing \"a listener asked us last week/earlier this week which Democratic primary candidates actually oppose sanctuary policy on illegal immigration\" used as a setup line — appears verbatim or near-verbatim in both 2026-04-28 ep1 and 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - The Evan Glass bill requiring background screening for DHS agents joining Montgomery County police — introduced and framed as the concrete sanctuary-policy example in 2026-04-28 ep1 and again in 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - The ICE agent mask-ban ordinance passed by the Montgomery County Council — covered as the sanctuary-policy benchmark in 2026-04-29 ep2\n  - \"Two stories, properly worked through\" / \"two stories, not spreading thin across six\" as an episode-framing device — used in 2026-04-29 ep1\n  - Governor Moore's \"Leave No One Behind\" slogan contrasted with disability services cuts — used in 2026-04-27 ep1 and ep1.rewrite\n  - The ACA marketplace quiet-downgrade story (\"thousands of Marylanders have been quietly downgrading their health insurance plans\") — introduced in 2026-04-28 ep1 and revisited in 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - Maryland's 90-day part-time legislature explanation (\"they meet in Annapolis for ninety days, the rest of the time they're lawyers, teachers, small business owners\") — used in 2026-04-26 ep3 and ep3.rewrite\n  - The wave of 25 Maryland lawmakers retiring or running for other offices framing — used in 2026-04-26 ep1, ep1.rewrite, and ep4\n  - The Beltsville Agricultural Research Center closure story as a District 19 candidate-record hook — used in 2026-04-27 ep4 and ep4.rewrite\n  - Listener's own frustration about promised candidate deep-dives not delivering — the show has now narrated this complaint back to the listener across at least five episodes; do not repeat it as a framing device again\n\nLISTENER POSITIONING:\n  • The listener is a first-time voter in the configured locale.\n  • Locale: Rockville, Montgomery County, Maryland.\n  • Their districts:\n  - U.S. Congressional District: MD-8\n  - MD Legislative District: 19\n  - MD State Senate District: 19\n  - MD House of Delegates District: 19\n  - Senatorial District: 19\n  - County Councilmanic District: 7\n  - Election District: 8\n  - Precinct: 08-008\n  - Circuit Court District: 6\n  - Appellate Circuit Court: 7\n  - School District: 005\n  - Party Central Committee: MCC19\n  • NEVER tell them to 'figure out who their candidate is', 'look up their district', or 'find out who's on their ballot'. The tool owns that work.\n  • The listener's recent daily_notes (in `context.listener_notes`) are direct asks — address at least ONE of them by name in this episode.\n\nBALLOT CONTEXT (already-known races):\nYOUR BALLOT (2026) — confirmed/likely candidates for the listener's districts. The listener's choice is BETWEEN these named people; never tell the listener to go figure out who their candidate is. If a contest has fewer than two known candidates, say so out loud (\"only one filer so far\") instead of fudging.\n  • Governor of Maryland\n      - Wes Moore (D)\n      - Andy Ellis (G)\n      - Chris Bouchat (R)\n      - Dan Cox (R)\n      - Ed Hale (R)\n      - Hershey (unknown) [withdrawn]\n  • Maryland House of Delegates District 19\n      - Bonnie Cullison (unknown) [withdrawn]\n      - Crutchfield (unknown)\n      - Kramer (unknown)\n      - Stewart (unknown)\n      - Tichy (unknown)\n  • Montgomery County Council District 7\n      - Dawn Luedtke (unknown)\n  • Montgomery County Executive\n      - Evan Glass (unknown)\n      - Friedson (unknown)\n      - Glass (unknown)\n      - Jawando (unknown)\n      - Will Friedson (unknown)\n\nPM SIGNAL BLOCK (what the listener cares about right now):\nListener rollup (2026-04-24..2026-04-30, based on 6 notes):\nSummary: This listener is a first-time Democratic voter in Rockville preparing for the June primary who cares most about knowing exactly who is on their ballot and what those candidates have actually done — voting records, bill history, and documented positions, not summaries or vibes. They have clear policy priors: skepticism toward high property taxes, opposition to increased education spending, openness to non-essential spending cuts and fiscal discipline, and a specific interest in which candidates oppose sanctuary policy on illegal immigration. They have flagged repeatedly that the show promises candidate deep-dives but fails to deliver them in a concrete, candidate-linked way.\nRecurring themes:\n  - Candidate voting records and historical public record — The listener has asked every single day for specific votes, old news, and documented positions tied to named candidates on their actual ballot, not general descriptions.\n  - Property taxes and fiscal discipline — The listener connects education spending votes directly to their property tax burden and has expressed support for fiscal restraint and cutting non-essential spending.\n  - Sanctuary policy and immigration enforcement — The listener wants to know concretely which Democratic primary candidates oppose or support sanctuary-style policies, not just which ones use immigration-friendly language.\n  - June primary ballot clarity — The listener is narrowing focus to actionable primary choices and wants episode content organized around who they can actually vote for in June.\nOpen questions the listener keeps raising:\n  - Who among the Democratic primary candidates actually opposes sanctuary policy on illegal immigration?\n  - Is Andrew Friedson the candidate who stands for fiscal restriction and spending discipline?\n  - Why does MCPS want to close and move Wootton High School, and what happens next?\n  - What is Kramer's full historical voting record, including old news and public records beyond recent sessions?\n  - What are the documented policy differences between each candidate on my primary ballot?\nTopics they want more coverage of:\n  - Andrew Friedson's specific fiscal record and positions — listener asked directly and has not received a focused answer\n  - Wootton High School closure — listener asked directly; scripts acknowledged it but did not resolve it\n  - Full historical background research on candidates (old news articles, public records, career-long voting history, not just recent session votes)\n  - Concrete side-by-side policy comparison of all Democratic primary candidates across the listener's specific races\nRECENT COVERAGE TO AVOID — do NOT reuse these framings, taglines, or anecdotes (they already shipped in the last 5 days):\n  - The framing \"a listener asked us last week/earlier this week which Democratic primary candidates actually oppose sanctuary policy on illegal immigration\" used as a setup line — appears verbatim or near-verbatim in both 2026-04-28 ep1 and 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - The Evan Glass bill requiring background screening for DHS agents joining Montgomery County police — introduced and framed as the concrete sanctuary-policy example in 2026-04-28 ep1 and again in 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - The ICE agent mask-ban ordinance passed by the Montgomery County Council — covered as the sanctuary-policy benchmark in 2026-04-29 ep2\n  - \"Two stories, properly worked through\" / \"two stories, not spreading thin across six\" as an episode-framing device — used in 2026-04-29 ep1\n  - Governor Moore's \"Leave No One Behind\" slogan contrasted with disability services cuts — used in 2026-04-27 ep1 and ep1.rewrite\n  - The ACA marketplace quiet-downgrade story (\"thousands of Marylanders have been quietly downgrading their health insurance plans\") — introduced in 2026-04-28 ep1 and revisited in 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - Maryland's 90-day part-time legislature explanation (\"they meet in Annapolis for ninety days, the rest of the time they're lawyers, teachers, small business owners\") — used in 2026-04-26 ep3 and ep3.rewrite\n  - The wave of 25 Maryland lawmakers retiring or running for other offices framing — used in 2026-04-26 ep1, ep1.rewrite, and ep4\n  - The Beltsville Agricultural Research Center closure story as a District 19 candidate-record hook — used in 2026-04-27 ep4 and ep4.rewrite\n  - Listener's own frustration about promised candidate deep-dives not delivering — the show has now narrated this complaint back to the listener across at least five episodes; do not repeat it as a framing device again\n\nWrite the full dialogue to `output_file`. Plain text only.",
